{
  "doc_id": "18737",
  "text": "Previous research has shown that J20 AD mice are able to perform successfully on the SOR task up to 15-16 months of age, with a delay between sample and test phases of up to one hour [CITATION_1] . If the delay is increased to four hours, the J20 mice become impaired at a younger age of 2-3 months [CITATION_2] or six to eight months [7] depending on the exact task protocol. If the delay is further increased to 24 hours, the J20 mice are unable to discriminate between novel and familiar objects from as young as four months of age [CITATION_3] . Although it appears that J20 mice experience impairments in recognition memory both as they age, and with an increased demand on memory through longer delays, it is unclear how much of this impairment can be attributed to age, the length of the delay, and the disease progression.",
